{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16877"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16877"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.23,0.06,0.02,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9567"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54125"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9857"},{"type":"tags","id":"9865"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22595"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary determinant of cardiac contractility?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intracellular calcium concentration","Resting sarcomere length","Mitochondrial ATP stores","Membrane sodium concentration","Diastolic filling time"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary determinant of cardiac contractility is the\u003Cstrong\u003E intracellular calcium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E. Higher calcium levels during systole allow for more \u003Cstrong\u003Ecross-bridge formation between actin and myosin, resulting in stronger contractions.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResting sarcomere length\u003C/strong\u003E - This determines preload and affects stroke volume via the Frank-Starling mechanism, but does not directly determine contractility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembrane sodium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - While sodium is important for the action potential, it does not directly determine the force of contraction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial ATP stores\u003C/strong\u003E - While ATP is necessary for contraction, it is not the primary determinant of contractility in normal physiological conditions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiastolic filling time\u003C/strong\u003E - This affects preload but does not directly determine the intrinsic contractile force\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiac contractility is primarily determined by intracellular calcium concentration during systole.","Increased contractility results in a greater force of contraction without changing the resting length of cardiac muscle.","Positive inotropes increase contractility by raising intracellular calcium levels."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physio